05804nam a22009015i 9781641894913DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97816418949137 a10.1515/97816418949132doi  a(DE-B1597)600375  a(OCoLC)1311464653  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-LDS 7aLIT0080102bisacsh04a895.11/0422300aReading Fu Poetry :bFrom the Han to Song Dynasties /ced. by Nicholas Morrow Williams. 1aLeeds : bARC Humanities Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (226 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEast Meets West: East Asia and Its Periphery from 200 BCE to 1600 CE00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGEMENTS -- tPREFACE -- tChapter 1 INVENTING THE FU: SIMULATED SPONTANEITY IN SIMA XIANGRU’S “GREAT MAN” -- tChapter 2 A PROBLEMATIC FU OF THE WESTERN HAN: THE “SHU DU FU” ATTRIBUTED TO YANG XIONG -- tChapter 3 A RECLUSE’S FRUSTRATION? RECONSIDERING YU XIN’S (513–581) “FU ON A SMALL GARDEN” -- tChapter 4 YUEFU AND FU: WANG BO’S NEW PROSODY FOR “SPRING LONGINGS” -- tChapter 5 LI QINGZHAO’S RHAPSODY ON CAPTURE THE HORSE -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe fu genre (or “rhapsody” in English) is one of the major genres of Chinese poetry throughout imperial history. This volume presents close readings of representative works in the genre, spanning over a millennium of its history. Each chapter contains a complete translation of major fu poems, accompanied by an essay presenting the work or works in historical context and also examining their significance in contemporary culture. Ranging in style and topic from the exuberant accumulation of detail in Yang Xiong’s “Shu Capital,” translated by David R. Knechtges, to the luscious lyricism of Wang Bo’s “Spring Longings,” translated by Timothy W. K. Chan, the poems present a panorama of how the genre has been used for both personal and social expression. While the individual essays examine their respective subjects in depth and detail, collectively the essays also offer a sweeping survey of the fu genre from the Han (206 B.C.E.–220 C.E.) through the Song (960–1279 C.E.) dynasty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aFuxHistory and criticism. 0aFu. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Chinese.2bisacsh  aChinese literature.  afu poetry.  amedieval literature.1 aChan, Timothy Wai Keung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgan, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnechtges, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuo, Yiyi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Nicholas Morrow, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliams, Nicholas Morrow, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074322708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076709408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2z978311074335708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2022 Part 2z978311076700108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022 Englishz978311099375208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022z9783110993